node.text: Love how you broke this down. Do you do workshops?

my response to a question I get multiple times a week: “how do I become a sexuality doula/sex educator like you?” note that all I’m talking about in this thread has nothing to do with academia or degrees, with certificates or thick books (though those can help). this is about core values, personal integrity and accountability, and deep study that can only be found in the very personal journey of our own sexual healing and liberation. anyone can read a book—but do they embody the work? do they put their body where their politics are? do they walk their talk? and if so, what specific actions are they taking within that walk?

I implore budding sex educators to interrogate within themselves why they’re feeling led to this field, to really pick apart the reasons why, and to ask themselves how they’re going to contribute to dismantling the -isms within their education work.

also: give props, gratitude, and respect to the sex educators who you’re inspired by and have been out here doing this unglamorous work for decades. they have pioneered these paths with their philosophies and frameworks that you are tripping over yourself to walk on. never forget that you wouldn’t even be contemplating getting into sex education if it weren’t for them. (and remember that there is a fine fine line between ‘inspiration’ and intellectual property theft.) and ask your fave sex educator (the one who perhaps your gut is telling you might not be totally grounded): “What are you doing to actively decolonize your own sexuality?” observe and study their answer, if they are able to answer. that will tell you everything about their politics, their values, their range. there is no shame in not being able to answer this question; we’re all in our own journeys. but I do think that question can help illuminate the areas where one might not be as holistic or well-rounded.

and lastly—don’t judge a person’s sexual education prowess by their follower count. some of the best sex educators in the world are the ones you’ve never heard of.
This is a really beautiful post. Thank you for this 💖

So so so important. I applaud you & your work, Evyan!!! This post puts words to a feeling I have time & time again while viewing "sex posi" folks who fall so short from an understanding of the realm of sexual healing as deeply naunced & undeniably rooted in dimantling systemic oppression. You leading this discussion - your words, your work, just you - amaze me! So grateful for the perspective you share 🙏

Where do I start... the word “decolonization” says it all. I thought I needed sex ed because my parents could even talk about periods, never mind anything having to do with sex - or even saying the word itself. In my late 20s I finally walked away from hardline evangelicalism after years of experiencing spiritual, sexual, and other types of trauma. In the ensuing years I realized that what I really needed was sex ed that reframed my ENTIRE FUCKING WORLDVIEW. Coming to terms with my sex nature, my body, my own desires, my history, my hurt, my physiological trauma responses... that is the sex education I need and that I’m pursuing. I’m finding that the freedom that comes from the healing is what has unleashed my wildest, most sensual, most sending self. Tips and tricks, that’s all well and good. But the deconstruction of all the beliefs - enculturated patriarchy and Christianity, the unfounded shame, etc. - that is how I am coming into my own. Thank you for this post. You said everything I needed to hear.
Absolutely love this post, so many people need to see this 🙌
This is the work I want to do and to help others do. Thank you for your insight!
Ooooooosh real talk👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼 love you Evyan

@evyan.whitney I just completed a Sex and Disability Training last week, and it was not easy at all. I passed my Certification test, but I still have a lot of Independent studying to do and I eventually want to get ASSECT Certified.

And: prepare yourself for all the not so pretty, not Instagram-y parts of it because sex isn’t always pretty. And what we’ve learnt through years of porn and over sexualisation is just not the truth #waddletothebathroom
Say it louder for those in the back!!
Sex education is never fun, you’re always the subject of ridicule and being overly sexualized.
Love how you broke this down. Do you do workshops?
